The "Getty Deposit" is located on contiguous land to the immediate northwest of the Scotia Mine deposit on lands presently set aside by the provincial government (Figure 3). The deposit was discovered at approximately the same time as the Scotia Mine deposit by a joint venture enterprise consisting of Getty Mining Northeast Limited and Skelly Mining Company.

A potentially viable lead zinc deposit was outlined which, although perhaps not economic on its own, might prove successful if incorporated as part of the ScoZinc overall resources. Both open pit and underground areas of potential development have been defined.

Drilling activity defined potential lead-zinc ore in one, possibly two, open pitable zones and in two possible underground zones. The deposit overlies a northward projecting segment of the Meguma greywacke high that continues south-westerly through the Carrolls Corner area. An irregular conglomeratic and breccia unit at the base of the Windsor Group locally overlies the basement and is in places interbedded with units at the base of the overlying carbonate section. Thicknesses as great as 30 metres are attained in what may represent talus-type deposition. The conglomerate is composed of angular to sub-rounded and unsorted Meguma Group lithologies cemented by finely crystalline dolostone. The contact with overlying carbonates of the Windsor Group is often gradational with Meguma clasts decreasing in quantity upwards until only carbonate is present.

### 15.1 Geology

When Mississippian seas covered this area, the biogenic activity was concentrated along, around and on top of this and other basement highs. Local reefal development occurred and it is mainly within these reefal carbonates that the lead-zinc mineralisation is located. The carbonates are predominantly dolostone. Buff to grey, finely bedded algal units account for much of the carbonate accumulation. Irregular zones rich in brachiopod, gastropod and bryozoa assemblages and algal stromatolites and coral growth account for the remainder of the carbonate build-up.

The northward projecting, undulating reefal structure now covers an area approximately 1,250 metres east-west by 600 metres north-south. The reef developed along the flanks of, and eventually over most of the Meguma basement high during early Mississippian time. Carbonate accumulations are minor near the axis of the basement high and then to a maximum of approximately 40 metres on the flanks. The reef may have extended much higher prior to erosion. From the present maximum thickness along the flanks the carbonates rapidly thin basin ward to less than 2 metres within a lateral distance of as little as 60 to 70 metres. Further out from the basement high the carbonate grades laterally into muddy carbonate, limy shale, mudstone and non-calcareous sandstones.

A thick evaporitic sequence with minor shale and carbonate beds pinches out against the reefal carbonates overlying the basement high. As a result, the evaporite beds are usually thinnest near the Meguma high and rapidly thicken with distance away from the reef.Although the evaporite beds are thin or absent on top of the basement high, the thickness exceeds 400 metres about 1 kilometre of the seaward side of the reefal complex.

The deposit is overlain completely by poorly sorted glacial till, the thickness of which ranges from 3 metres to 100 metres. The maximum thicknesses are encountered in the evaporite pinch-out zone.

# 15.2 Mineralisation

Lead-zinc mineralisation has been delineated within three separate zones on the original Getty/Skelly lands but confined to a more or less continuous reefal complex. The Southeast mineralised zone lies immediately south of the village of Gays River and is an extension of the original Gays River deposit. Both the central and southwest zones are west of the main highway. The central zone is crescent-shaped and conforms to the shape of the reefal complex developed around the northerly protruding paleo-topographic high. Minor mineralisation has been located between the three main zones.

Sulphide mineralisation is found throughout the reefal carbonate complex as well as in the carbonate matrix of the underlying conglomeratic unit. Galena and sphalerite are the main sulphide minerals with pyrite, marcasite and chalcopyrite present in minor to trace amounts. Strong zones of mineralisation occur throughout all sections of the conglomeratic and reefal rock units with no apparent preference for specific horizons. There is, however, a tendency for the higher grade mineralisation to occur along the flanks of the carbonate reef which appears to represent the general fore-reef area. The Gays River deposit also contains its more massive mineralised zones along the fore-reef area to the northwest of the reefal trend with lesser amounts of ore-grade material along the reef crest.

The sphalerite is honey yellow to light buff, finely crystalline and generally tends to occur as irregular disseminations in weak to intense concentrations varying from discrete segregated crystals to concentrations greater than $10 \%$ but can also occur as semi-massive to massive seams along bedding planes, coating fossils, and infilling vugs.

Galena is less abundant than sphalerite and often occurs as fine to medium size cubic crystals. It is found throughout the carbonate and conglomeratic sections most commonly as irregular disseminations in high to low concentrations as discrete crystals to concentrations greater than $10 \%$. It also commonly occurs as irregular veins and semi-massive to massive seams.

Based on a $1.5 \%$ zinc-equivalent cut-off grade $(1 \% \mathrm{~Pb}=0.6 \% \mathrm{Zn}$ in 1975 and a minimum core length of 3 metres) resources at the Getty deposit were estimated by Hudgins and Lamb (1992) at 4.5 million tons at an average grade of $1.3 \% \mathrm{~Pb}$ and $1.9 \% \mathrm{Zn} .^{7}$

### 17.1 Surface Resources

### 17.1.1 General

The deposit is characterised by complex geometry and is difficult to model in terms of standard techniques. Lying along a 'paleo-shoreline', it features repetitive changes in strike of $90^{\circ}$ and more around a general trend of $060^{\circ}$ Azimuth, and with varying dip.

The deposit has been mined by underground methods in the past and is therefore intersected by numerous openings along the hanging wall contact. This geometry makes it difficult to incorporate the true spatial relationship of the samples for estimation purposes without the use of 'unfolding' techniques that transform the sample data into another co-ordinate space that honours the spatial relationships. Variography and estimation are conducted in the transformed space, and the results are then back-transformed into the original space.

### 17.1.2 Geological Modelling Approach

The drill-hole data entered in the database was displayed in 3D graphics mode (G4W), and a number of triangulated surfaces (TINs or Triangulated Irregular Networks) were created to represent the base of the overburden, and the lower and upper contacts of the carbonate (ore) horizon. The surfaces were developed by selecting the relevant down-the-hole intersects (with interactive inspection and adjustment), and calculating a best-fit plane through the data points derived. The selection process for the underground holes was complicated by the fact that some holes were drilled from footwall to hanging-wall, and some in the opposite direction. To assist in differentiating the contacts, a new field (T/B) was added to the Geology table of the database to contain a numeric code designating the contact as either a top or bottom contact. Codes were also defined to designate carbonate intervals that were either the first or the last interval in a hole, indicating that the hole had been either collared or ended in carbonate. The codes were calculated by a formula in the original Excel spreadsheets and then merged into the 'T/B' field in the Geology table. The drill-holes were grouped by orientation (vertical up, vertical down and inclined) to further facilitate this process. A smooth 3D surface through the active data was then created by Laplace interpolation, relative to the best-fit plane.

Topographic contour data derived from the AutoCAD drawing files provided was utilised to create a TIN of the original topography over the project area.A 3D solid of the carbonate formation was initially created from the top and bottom surfaces developed above. In the initial absence of detailed geologic plans and sections, the surfaces used were based solely on drill hole intersections. The drill holes utilised were the surface holes, up-holes from underground, and horizontal underground holes that had clearly defined 'top' and 'bottom' contacts, as designated by the 'TJB" numeric code described above. A set of 3D solid models of the existing underground development and stope areas developed by Mr. Bruce Hudgins of Hudgtec Consultants was imported from the AutoCAD DXF files provided. It should be noted that these solids could not be validated in G4W, indicating that they were probably not completely closed. This problem again reflects the complexity of the models, but does not significantly affect the results of volume determinations or block model 'stamping' in G4W.

Subsequent Inspection of the 3D solid in section and plan indicated that although the overall geometry of the deposit was being honoured, there were significant variances from existing manual interpretations and underground mapping in a number of areas. After a number of reinterpolations utilising both drill-hole and digitised data, it was concluded that inconsistencies in lithological coding in the drill holes would negate the contact modelling approach.

It was further decided that manual interpretation was required, and that the ore zone be differentiated into a high-grade massive sulphide zone and a low-grade disseminated zone. Drill-hole data and underground openings were then plotted on hard-copy plans at ten metre intervals, and interpretations of the high-grade zone, the low-grade and the hanging-wall 'Trench' were produced. The cut-off grades that were for the high- grade and low-grades zones were $7 \% \mathrm{Zn}-\mathrm{Eq}$ and $2 \% \mathrm{Zn}-\mathrm{Eq}$ respectively. These values were selected to correspond with cut-offs utilised in earlier resource evaluations. The plan-view interpretations were digitised as closed polygons, then tied together in the solids modelling system to create separate 3D solid models of the high-grade, low-grade and trench zones of the deposit. This work was completed by Mr. Peter Irwin, of Resource Data Management Inc., under contract to Savage Resources Canada Co. The geometric complexity of the deposit is reflected in the large number of tie lines required to adequately control the triangulation process utilised to create 3D solid models. The modelling was, therefore, time consuming but produced valid solids for the ore and trench zones. These models were adopted for use during the previous resource estimate in 1998 (Carew, 1998) and again for the current resource estimate.

# 17.1.3 "Unfolding" Process

As stated in Section 17.1.1, the deposit is characterised by complex geometry and is difficult to model in terms of standard techniques. An 'unfolding' technique was used that transformed the sample data into another co-ordinate space while honouring the spatial relationships.

The Gemcom ${ }^{\circledR}$ unfold application was used for the transformation in this case. This approach is based on the concept of slabs - a slab being a region of space that is topologically equivalent to a cube. The edges are 3D polylines and are not necessarily straight from end to end. Each face is defined by four polylines on its perimeter and the nominally vertical edges of the slab may also have more than two points. The geological feature of interest, e.g. a folded and/or faulted vein or seam is broken down into a collection of adjacent slabs, the onlyproviso being that any two adjacent slabs must share an entire common face. The algorithm highlights three of the edge polylines of a representative slab that are nominally orthogonal and allows them to be associated with $\mathrm{X}, \mathrm{Y}$ and Z axes of the unfolded space. All of the polylines are then categorised into three sets of lines corresponding to these unfolded axes. The unfolded slabs are displayed below the original polylines, and the unfolded lines will be aligned approximately to the $\mathrm{X}, \mathrm{Y}$, and Z axes. The average length of each of the sets is calculated and a nominal graticule size, or spacing, is entered. The unfolding transformation includes two graticules - one for the folded region and one for the unfolded region. The points in the two graticules have an exact 1:1 correspondence, which provides for a check that the transformation will be reasonable. If any graticule cells are highly skewed, for example, the folded region can be subdivided into smaller slabs. In addition, the interior vertices can be allowed to slide on the various sets of lines in order to minimise distortion.

The graticule points are simply samples of the transformation, and are connected by straight lines to make the visualisation easier. Various combinations of the sliding axes can be experimented with, particularly in cases where the polyline lengths along the feature are different, in order to minimise the distortion in these cases. The 3D polylines were generated by contouring the 3D solid of the mineralised carbonate developed for the deposit in earlier studies at 10 m plan intervals, as the original polylines are no longer available. These polylines were subdivided into a series of smaller adjacent slabs corresponding to the alternating strike direction of the deposit. A section showing the slabs and the allocation of the association with the unfolded axes is illustrated in Figure 16. The unfolded space is illustrated later in Figure 21 .
![img-17.jpeg](img-17.jpeg)

Figure 16: 3D Polyline slabs and axes.

The basic procedure is as follows:

- Creation of the unfolding transformation;- Forward transformation (unfold) of the sample data points;
- Variography and block modelling in the transformed space;
- Back-transformation of the estimated block data ( Zn and Pb ) into normal (folded) space; and,
- Allocation of the values to a block model in normal (folded) space by nearest neighbour interpolation.


# 17.1.4 Drillhole Data

A subset of the overall drillhole database was utilised for estimation purposes, comprising those drill holes that intersected the 3D solid model of the carbonate mineralisation. This subset comprises 623 holes and includes both surface and underground drilling.

### 17.1.5 Mineralised Envelope

The mineralised envelope for estimation purposes was restricted to the carbonate material within the 3D solid models created from plan view interpretations. These interpretations and 3D model are regarded as the most representative constraints on the mineralisation available. Separate 3D models were developed for the low grade, disseminated portion of the deposit, and for the less continuous high grade zone that lies along the footwall contact, and which was exploited by previous underground mining.

### 17.1.6 Statistical Analysis and Capping

The sample sets for zinc and lead mineralisation comprised those assay intervals falling within the 3D solids and were compiled separately for the low-grade (LG) and high-grade (HG) zones. The sample statistics, histograms and probability plots are shown in Figure 17 and Figure 18.

While both Zn and Pb assay grades exhibit fairly typical positively skewed distributions, the Pb values exhibit evidence of a multi-modal distribution, with a set of values falling in the 0.01 to $0.1 \%$ range - this may be related to the use of arbitrary and variable values for detection limits in the Pb data. In general, Zn and Pb values are not particularly well correlated, with a correlation coefficient of 0.32 . There is also some evidence of possible misclassification of some values between low grade and high grade zones in both cases, either in terms of original typing, or in geometric boundary effects relative to the 3D solids. The Zn values are generally well behaved, with relatively low Coefficients of Variation (COV), whereas the Zn values exhibit a relatively high COV.

Whereas initial studies on the deposit by Savage Resources Canada Co. considered a capping value of $13 \%$ on both Zn and Pb , examination of the probability plots indicates that although the number of high values steadily decreases, the upper tail for the all distributions are fairly continuous and unbroken up to values considerably higher than this, suggesting that higher capping values could be utilised. In later studies, discussions with Savage personnel led to an alternative approach in which the high-grade outliers in the distributions were retained in thedata set prior to any compositing, but severely restricted in terms of interpolation. Block centroids were required to be within 5 metres of the sample before it could be used in the estimation of the block in question. Given the indication that higher capping values could be considered, and to maintain consistency, this approach was retained for this study. No grade capping was applied prior to compositing, but the range restriction was subsequently applied in estimation for Zn and Pb composites above $26 \%$.![img-18.jpeg](img-18.jpeg)

Equal length composites were prepared from uncut assay values in a two step process. Initial composite intervals were defined from the intercepts of the drill holes with the high-grade and low-grade 3D solids of the mineralised zone. Equal length composites of 1.5 metres were then generated within these intervals - 1.5 metres is approximately the average length of the assay intervals. Residual intervals of less than 1.5 metres at the top and bottom contacts were retained if the length was at least $0.6 \mathrm{~m}(40 \%$ of composite length). Intervals less than 0.6 m in length were discarded. The low-grade composites set was further subdivided into those falling below 490 m elevation (below which the deposit dips at varying angles) and those above 490 m where the deposit is essentially flat-lying. The composite statistics and histograms for the overall high grade and low grade Zn and Pb are shown in Figure 19.

No evidence of specific gravity test work was available. Therefore, a formula for specific gravity based on zinc and lead grades was used for the mineralised zones. This formula, which was also used by Savage Resources for their 1998 resource estimate, was:

$$
\mathrm{SG}=1 /(\mathrm{Pb} \% /(86.6 \times 7.6)+\mathrm{Zn} \% /(67.0 \times 4.0)+(1-\mathrm{Pb} \% / 86.6-\mathrm{Zn} \% / 67.0) / 2.7)
$$

A default density of $2.7 \mathrm{t} / \mathrm{m}^{3}$ was utilised for mineralisation where grade data was not available. The densities utilised for other materials were:

Two block models were constructed for interpolation purposes, a primary model in normal (un-transformed) space, and a secondary, smaller model in transformed space for interpolation of the un-folded data. The primary block model was defined to cover the volume of interest, and has the following Gemcom ${ }^{\circledR}$ parameters:

| Columns: | 160 |

The primary block model is configured as a 'partial' block model, which allows the percentage of various rock types within the block to be stored and utilised for manipulation and reporting purposes. The rock type model was initialised with the default rock code for air and all blocks below the topographic surface were set to the Evaporites (gypsum) rock code. The model was then overprinted with rock codes for the overburden, Trench and Goldenville (quartzite) using 3D solids created from surfaces and sectional interpretations. This rock type model is referred to as the 'Standard' rock type model. The final step was overprinting with rock codes for the existing U/G mining excavations, the high-grade (HG) carbonate and the low-grade (LG) carbonate. The percentage of these three material types in blocks intersecting the solids was calculated and stored separately, with the excavations having the highest priority, and the high-grade zone the next highest priority, in blocks where the solids overlapped. This procedure ensures that the mined-out material in the model is correctly accounted for. The rock code for any other material in these blocks was taken from the standard rock type model, i.e. a block on the hanging wall contact might comprise $50 \% \mathrm{U} / \mathrm{G}$ excavation, $20 \% \mathrm{HG}$ carbonate and $30 \%$ Trench material.The 3D solid of the existing U/G excavations was generated by Mr. Bruce Hudgins of Hudgtec Consulting and was supplied by ScoZinc. The 3D solids of the HG and LG zones were generated by Mr. Peter Irwin of Resource Data Management, Inc. from plan interpretations. Zinc equivalent cut-offs of $2 \%$ and $7 \%$ were utilised for the LG and HG zones, respectively in developing the interpretations.

# 17.2 Underground Resources - Northeast Zone

Resources in the Northeast Zone were estimated. Because it was determined that this area would be most profitably mined using underground mining methods, a cut-off grade of $5 \%$ zinc equivalent was used to outline the mineralisation on sections spaced fifty metres apart. To permit mechanised mining, the minimum mining width and height were both 2.4 metres. An additional 0.1 metre "skin" dilution was incorporated into the resource outlines. This resulted in a widening of the outline beyond the grade cut-off point. Although the dilution material was below cut-off, in most cases it contained some metal.

The section outlines were drawn under the assumption that selective mining could be carried out within the carbonate. Meaning, it would be possible to mine along either the footwall or the hanging wall contact rather than mining the full width of the carbonate unit.

To determine the quantity of material, the outline area on each section was multiplied by its strike length (fifty metres) to determine the volume. That figure was multiplied by an average SG of 2.9 to determine mass. To determine grade, the length-weighted average grade and the true width of each intercept was calculated. The average section grade was determined by calculating the true-length-weighted average grade of all of the section's intercepts. The average true width of the intercepts was also calculated.

One contiguous body made up the underground resources that lie northeast and along strike from the proposed pit (Figure 26). Cross-sections showing the resource outline are shown in Figure 27 through Figure 29. The average grade of each body was determined by calculatingthe average-true-width-weighted grade of the sections that made up the body. The average true width of the body was determined by calculating the volume-weighted average true section width.

Because of the 20-30 m sample spacing and the lack of bulk or underground sampling in this area, these Resources were classified as Indicated Resources. Indicated Resources in the Northeast Underground Zone were estimated to be 1,110,000 tonnes containing $6.6 \%$ zinc and $3.7 \%$ lead. The average true width was estimated to be 3.6 metres (Table 23).

Prior to 2004, very little sampling and assaying for gypsum was done. Past drilling campaigns focused solely on zinc and lead. Prior to 2004, much of the gypsum core was saved; however, much of it was improperly stored and the gypsum weathered away.

In 2004, fourteen vertical holes were drilled that penetrated the gypsum resource. These holes, which are shown in Figure 15, were sampled and assayed for gypsum. Most of the samples were also assayed for chloride. The chloride assay was for all chlorides - chloride ions from any source.

Examination of the core revealed that the gypsum was relatively hard and pure. There were very few clay interbeds as appear at National Gypsum's deposit in nearby Milford. The gypsum graded into anhydrite, typical of Nova Scotia gypsum deposits. There was no clear contact between the two rock types.

A preliminary assessment of gypsum quality was carried out using the holes that were drilled in 2004. A cut-off grade of $85 \%$ gypsum was used. Where the hole entered the gypsum was defined as the top contact. Where the hole left the gypsum, meaning where the hole left the gypsum horizon and passed into material with an average gypsum grade of less than $85 \%$ (in other words, into anhydrite), was defined as the bottom contact.

The average gypsum thickness was 31 metres with a range of 9-85 metres. The gypsum was covered by 16-61 metres of overburden, averaging 38 metres. The average stripping ratio was 1.7.

The subset of samples within the gypsum consisted of sixty-nine (69) samples from fourteen holes. More than half of these samples ( 44 of them) were also assayed for chloride. The length-weighted average grade was $93 \%$ gypsum. The length-weighted average chloride content was 43 ppm . Only one sample contained over 100 ppm chloride - this sample averaged 142 ppm over three metres.Table 21: Raw (non-weighted) assay statistics.

The reader should note that this analysis represents only an arithmetic analysis of gypsum quality and chloride content. No spatial statistics were calculated. Therefore, this is only an indication of gypsum quality - not an accurate estimate. The gypsum sample spacing is currently too wide for meaningful calculation of Resources or Reserves.

There are many bags of sample rejects available for mineral processing work. These are stored at the Scotia Mine site. Also, the core was sawed in half for sampling and the remaining halves were stored in a dry facility. The sample pulps are also readily available for further assay work.![img-31.jpeg](img-31.jpeg)

### 18.1 Surface Reserves

To estimate the Surface Reserves, an optimised pit shell was generated from the block model utilising Whittle 3.4 pit optimisation software. Tim Carew, P.Geo., carried out the optimisation process using a set of economic and geotechnical parameters that were supplied by Mr. Douglas Roy, P.Eng of MineTech International Limited. Only blocks in the Measured and Indicated Resource categories were used. The base case economic and geotechnical parameters were:

A surface mine plan, complete with haul roads, was designed using the optimum pit shells as a guide (Figure 31). Table 22 reports the Reserves that are contained within the pit design. Figure 32 shows a grade-tonnage curve for diluted, recoverable, Proven and Probable Reserves.

Using a $0.75 \%$ zinc-equivalent cut-off grade, diluted, recoverable Proven Reserves total 1.8 million tonnes containing $3.2 \%$ zinc and $1.3 \%$ lead. Probable Reserves total 1.7 million tonnes containing $2.9 \%$ zinc and $1.2 \%$ lead. Proven + Probable Reserves total 3.4 million tonnes containing $2.9 \%$ zinc and $1.2 \%$ lead.

In-Pit Inferred Resources total 510,000 tonnes containing $2.2 \%$ zinc and $1.1 \%$ lead. The reader should note that in-pit Inferred Resources cannot be considered Reserves.![img-32.jpeg](img-32.jpeg)

### 19.1 Mining Operations

### 19.1.1 Initial Surface Mining

For the first few years, mining will be by surface methods using standard methods of drilling, blasting, and excavating using excavators and truck haulage. An equipment list is reported in Table 25. This equipment will be leased from a local dealer. The pit will have an oval shape with its long axis oriented along the northeast-southwest strike of the deposit. To the northeast, the pit is constrained by Gays River and Highway 224. Gays River will be diverted slightly to allow the pit to expand toward the highway.

The pit haul road will traverse the footwall of the deposit, generally along the carbonate/quartzite contact. The overall pit slope angle for the footwall will be less than $45^{\circ}$. The gypsum/anhydrite evaporite hanging wall is more stable, allowing a steeper overall slope angle of $55^{\circ}$. Overburden slope angles will be kept below a $2: 1$ grade $\left(27^{\circ}\right)$. The overcompacted Trench clay will also be kept below a $2: 1$ grade $\left(27^{\circ}\right)$. A complete description of geotechnical work is reported in Section 19.4.

Working benches in ore will be five metres high for grade control purposes. Final bench heights in ore will be up to twenty metres. Higher benches, up to twenty metres high, taken in one or more cuts, are planned for the hanging wall evaporites.

After the pit reaches an elevation of approximately 480 metres (approximately 50 metres depth), underground development can begin from a portal in the northeast end of the pit, extending along strike to the northeast.

### 19.1.2 Underground Mining

A main haulage drift will be established on the 480 metre level. It will extend from the pit along strike to the northeast. It will pass underneath the river but it will be entirely situated within the competent footwall quartzites. A second decline and portal will be located at thenortheast end of the Underground Reserves to provide a second access for the underground workings.

The weak hanging wall Trench clay poses the greatest technical challenge to underground mining. The Trench material is relatively strong for clay because it is overconsolidated (compacted). However, groundwater influx weakens it and also poses a dewatering challenge. As part of minimising the operational and safety hazards posed by the weak Trench clay, dewatering operations will lower the groundwater table below the active mine workings.

The cut-and-fill mining method was chosen specifically to address the weak hanging wall issue. It will be mechanised, meaning drill jumbos will do the development and production drilling. LHD's (Load-Haul-Dump vehicles) will muck the broken rock back to re-muck stockpile bays. In narrower stopes, slushers may be used to muck the broken rock. Underground dump trucks will haul the rock to surface.

From the main haulage drift on the 480 metre level, the main ramp will spiral downwards on the footwall side of the stope (Figure 34). A "lift ramp" will extend from the main ramp downward to Lift 1, approximately twenty metres from the planned top of the stope.

The mining method is a modified form of mechanised cut and fill mining. It is a combination of undercut and fill and conventional (overhand) cut and fill mining. Lift 1 (Figure 34) will be five metres high, at least 2.5 metres wide and its along strike length will be limited by ground conditions and haulage efficiencies. Generally, cut and fill lifts can be as long as two hundred metres. The overall stope height will be a maximum of eighty metres.

Every 50-100 metres, as required, raises will be driven, in ore, upward from lower levels. These will provide valuable geologic information, grade information, alternate escape routes and ventilation pathways. During the fill cycle, cribbing will be built around the raises to keep them open.

When Lift 1 has finished, the fill cycle will begin. As no sill pillars will be left, Lift 1 fill will form the back for Lift 8 (Figure 34). Therefore, the first few metres of Lift 1's fill will contain a higher cement content (up to $15 \%$ cement:solids) and possibly some reinforcing material. The remaining fill will contain only enough cement (approximately $3 \%$ ) to hold together the aggregate fill, providing a stable floor on which to work. The aggregate in the fill will consist of sand and gravel that will be sourced from on-site glacial-fluvial deposits. It will be filled to within one-two metres of the back to allow for blasting swell during Lift 2 mining. Production will be accomplished using breasting. The mining will progress upwards to Lift 4 in the same manner. After Lift 4 has been filled, production will move to Lift 5 and the cycle will be continue.

The eastern half of the underground reserves lie under Gays River. If groundwater influx presents an unacceptable operational or safety hazard in this area, mining the first group of lifts (Lifts 1-4, Figure 34) in this area can be carried out during the drier months.![img-34.jpeg](img-34.jpeg)

Figure 34: Cross-sectional conceptual schematic of modified mechanised cut-and-fill mining method (showing lift sequence).

# 19.1.3 Dewatering

Mine dewatering will be important for both surface and underground mining, but particularly for underground mining. In the underground mine, prior to starting a new lift cycle, the ramp will be continued deeper so that sumps can be established. Typical of soils, the hanging wall Trench clay is stronger when it is dry. Therefore, dewatering operations will strive to maintain the local water table at a level lower than the current workings. This will also significantly reduce the possibility of a sudden inrush of water. In the past, dewatering operations removed an average 4,000 gallons per minute ( gpm ) from the underground workings. The flowrate ranged from as little as $2,000 \mathrm{gpm}$ in drier months to $6,000 \mathrm{gpm}$ in months with heavier precipitation.

A significant portion of the inflow to the mine was groundwater recharge from Gays River. The river diversion plan includes lining part of the river with clay, which should reduce the recharge flowrate.

Drainage from backfilling operations is not expected to form a significant component of the overall dewatering requirement.

### 19.2 Mine Dilution and Recovery

Dilution was estimated at $15 \%$. The amount of ore that will be recovered from the mine was estimated at $90 \%$.# 19.3 Mineral Processing Operations

The Scotia Mine processing plant was constructed during the late 1970's by Canada Wide Mines (Esso) (Figure 35). Esso operated for less than two years during the period 1979-1981. Seabright converted the mill to process gold during the mid-to-late 1980's. Westminster later re-converted and updated the mill to process zinc and lead, then operated it for a short time during the period 1989-1991. In all, 740,000 tonnes of zinc and lead ore have been processed in the mill (Table 9).

From a stockpile adjacent to the mill, a wheel loader loads ore into the primary jaw crusher (Figure 36). It is further crushed to $-1 / 2$ inch and stored in a fine ore bin. From there, it passes to the grinding mills, then to a lead flotation section. The ore, with most of the galena (lead sulphide or PbS ) removed, passes to the sphalerite (zinc sulphide or ZnS ) flotation section. The zinc and lead concentrates are separately thickened, filtered and dried before being stockpiled for shipment to the smelter.
![img-35.jpeg](img-35.jpeg)

Figure 35: Views of the outside (left) and inside (right) of the mill.![img-36.jpeg](img-36.jpeg)

Figure 36: Process flowsheet.

Bulk concentrate will be stored on site. A front-end loader will be used to load concentrate into a highway semi-dump truck for the short trip to a railway siding in Milford, NS. Milford is eight kilometres along the highway from the mine site. The truck will dump from a ramp directly into gondola-style, 100 tonne railway cars. Canadian National will retrieve the cars and take them to the smelters. Lead concentrate will be taken Noranda's Belledune smelter in Northern New Brunswick and zinc concentrate will be taken to Noranda's Valleyfield smelter outside Montreal.# 19.3.1 Production Forecast

The mill has a nominal capacity of 1,350 tonnes per day of higher grade (greater than seven percent zinc), quartzite breccia ore. When processing lower grade, carbonate ore, the mill performs well at production rates as high as 2,000 tonnes per day (Thornton, 2006 (1)). A production rate of 2,000 tonnes per day is planned for the surface operation. Operating 350 days per year, that translates to 700,000 tonnes of ore per year (Table 26).

Stripping operations will start at the beginning of the fourth quarter of Year One. Milling will begin two months later, during the eleventh month of Year 1, after a sufficient amount of material has been stockpiled. Each year, surface operations will produce 30,000 tonnes of zinc concentrate and 10,000 tonnes of lead concentrate.

Because of the higher grade of the underground ore, a production rate of 1,350 tonnes per day is planned for the underground operation. This is so as not to overwhelm the filtering and drying sections of the mill. Operating 350 days per year, that translates to 473,000 tonnes of ore per year Table 26). Each year, underground operations will produce 40,000 tonnes of zinc concentrate and 19,000 tonnes of lead concentrate.

The footwall at the carbonate/quartzite contact has an average dip of less than $45^{\circ}$. The haul road will also be incorporated into the footwall, further reducing the overall pit slope angle. The footwall consists of strong, competent quartzite with no major adverse geotechnical features such as faulting that are the major causes of slope instability. The overall slope will be less than $45^{\circ}$, which is more than adequate.

The hanging wall consists of gypsum/anhydrite evaporites and Trench clays. The Trench is wider near the surface and pinches at depth. Gypsum and anhydrite are strong, competent rocks that make for stable slopes. Evidence of this stability can be observed at National Gypsum's quarry in nearby Milford/Dutch Settlement. An overall slope angle of $55^{\circ}$ in evaporites is warranted. Trench clays are more competent than glacial till because they are over-compacted. A maximum grade of $2: 1$ is warranted. However, whenever possible, the Trench clay will be stripped flat, back to the evaporite contact.

The overburden consists of a thick mantle of clayey-glacial till with localised glacio-fluvial deposits (McKee and Hannon, 1985). It will be pushed back five metres from the edge of the pit and sloped at a maximum grade of 2:1. CBCL (1999) determined that the factor of safety was 1.5 using that grade. Loose surficial sands or soft silts will be graded under 2.5:1 (CBCL, 1999). The till stratum ranges in thickness from 10-40 m. It has been cut in turn by glacialfluvial deposits of sand, silty sand and gravel including the Gays River sediments. It was noted that fluvial sediments many contact the bedrock in some locations.

Aston and Lamb (1993) identified two main aquifers associated with the property. First is the Overburden Aquifer consisting of highly permeable fluvial-glacial coarse sands and gravels, interlaced with less permeable bands of fine sand and silt. Second is the Bedrock Aquifer with consists of highly permeable interconnected karstic gypsum cavities along with hydraulically connected but less permeable jointed and fractured carbonates and quartzites. The two aquifers are hydraulically connected in areas where the permeable overburden sediments are in contact with permeable bedrock zones.# 19.4.1 Underground Geotechnical Investigation of Trench Material

In 1981, Jacques, Whitford and Associates carried out a geotechnical investigation of the hanging wall Trench clay (Brown, 1981). They inspected three underground Trench exposures in the 101, 104 and 107 areas. They also drilled three surface boreholes using a power augur. Clay and rock samples were taken for laboratory testing.

They observed that the unsupported stand-up time for the Trench material is at least several days - an adequate length of time for installing ground support. They recommended that grouted soil anchors and wire mesh screen be installed to support underground Trench exposures. Shotcrete could be added as an additional stabilising feature, if and where conditions were particularly unstable.

They stressed that dewatering efforts must be sufficient to prevent pore pressure from developing around the opening, that blasting vibrations be within safe limits and that changes in the stress field caused by mining be within acceptable limits. They recommended that wherever shotcrete is employed, weep holes be provided to prevent hydrostatic pressures from building.

They carried out three direct shear tests on a sample of Trench clay and determined the shear strength to be:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \tau=16.5 \mathrm{kPa}+\sigma_{\mathrm{n}}^{\prime} \tan \left(23^{\circ}\right) \\
& \text { where: } \tau=\quad \text { shear strength }(\mathrm{kPa}) \\
& \sigma_{\mathrm{n}}^{\prime}=\text { normal stress }(\mathrm{kPa})
\end{aligned}
$$

### 19.5 Mine Water and River Diversion

Groundwater infiltration into the Scotia Mine has historically posed a safety hazard and an operational problem. Water decreases the strength of soil and rock masses. There have also been several high pressure inrushes of soil laden water. Mine dewatering operations typically removed $4,000 \mathrm{gpm}$, on average. When Gays River was high during spring flooding, up to 6,000 gpm was removed. Golder Associates (1992) determined that one-quarter to one-half of that water originated from Gays River, apparently due to seepage through the riverbed.

Several sinkholes have developed due to mine dewatering operations. Groundwater flow through the gypsum hanging-wall rocks cause rapid dissolution of the gypsum, creating karst features, the surface expression of which are sinkholes. These can present a hazard to equipment and personnel.

To allow the northeast end of the proposed open pit to expand closer toward Highway 224 and to decrease the water seepage from the river into the proposed mine, CBCL (1999) designed a minor diversion of Gays River after carrying out a geotechnical investigation. The design was based on a 1998 field investigation that included drilling twelve boreholes at six sites. At each site, they found a 1.2-1.8 m layer of surficial silt overlying interbedded, alluvial silt and sand.The recommended design consisted of digging a new channel for part of the river that would be separated from the pit by a dyke. Rather than using a single, wide dyke, CBCL recommended using two narrower dykes to mitigate the hazard of sinkholes causing damage to the dyke. Their rationale was that if sinkholes cause a breech in one dyke, the other would hold back the water.

The overall structure would be 600 metres long, fifty metres wide at the base and have a crest elevation of 519 metres. The dyke will be set back a minimum of ten metres from the top of the pit slope. The pit side of the dyke would have a $3: 1$ slope while the river side would have a 5:1 slope. Because of its low permeability, CBCL recommended that the dyke be constructed using the till that was stripped from the area of the pit. It should be built up in layers, allowing time for pore pressure to dissipate before placing the next layer. The riverbank would be lined with rip-rap for erosion control.

The new river channel would be lined with 60 centimetres of till to prevent water from seeping down through the riverbed. This will greatly reduce the amount of water that seeps into the mine workings.

# 19.6 Markets

The on-site processing plant will concentrate zinc and lead in mineral form (sphalerite and galena, respectively). These separate concentrates will be sold to one or more outside smelters within North America or overseas. The Scotia Mine concentrate is high in purity without any penalty-attracting impurities. Currently, world-wide smelter capacity is under-utilised and the demand for concentrate exceeds what the mines can supply. Therefore, there should be no trouble selling the concentrate.

The principal use for zinc is in galvanising, with continuous galvanised sheet demand accounting for around two-thirds of this. Other major uses are die-casting and brass goods and both these are used in a very wide range of manufactured goods. Galvanising applications are principally to be found in construction and automobiles. Investment in infrastructure and manufacturing facilities are important factors in this rapid expansion of consumption in China. Growth of global demand is estimated to have averaged $3.7 \%$ between 2000 and 2005; whilst Chinese consumption has increased by $16 \%$ on average over this period, growth has been much more modest in the rest of world, at only $0.6 \%$ (Roberts, 2006). Zinc demand outside China has suffered as a result of the rapid increase in China's exports of manufactured goods but, on the other hand, has benefited from China's need to import increasing quantities of galvanised sheet and die-casting alloys.

World-wide, approximately 10.7 million tonnes of refined zinc metal was consumed in 2005 (Roberts, 2006). Unlike zinc, where more than $90 \%$ of refined metal production derives directly from zinc and bulk concentrates, less than $40 \%$ of total refined lead production is produced directly from lead and bulk concentrates (Roberts, 2006). This is because the principal end use of lead, the manufacture of lead-acid batteries, accounts for $80 \%$ of total demand. The useful life of these batteries is rather short, typically no more than five or six years at best, and often shorter, and virtually all these batteries are recycled to recover thelead. Thus a large share of production increases in line with consumption, but with a lag of a few years. Essentially, mine production only needs to meet the incremental use of lead in batteries, and the remaining dissipative uses which currently account for only $20 \%$ of total demand.

World-wide, approximately 7.5 million tonnes of refined lead metal was consumed in 2005 (Roberts, 2006). The main use for lead is in the manufacture of lead-acid batteries used in almost all motor vehicles for starting, lighting and ignition (SLI batteries) and industrial batteries which have widespread application providing back-up, portable and motive power (Roberts, 2006). There has been good growth in global lead demand since 2003, albeit that most of this growth has been in China. With global economic growth expected to be sound over the next few years, demand growth is expected to continue.
![img-37.jpeg](img-37.jpeg)

World-wide zinc consumption (RBC, 2005).
![img-38.jpeg](img-38.jpeg)

World-wide lead consumption (Roberts, 2006).

While there are alternatives to lead-acid batteries, for the foreseeable future lead-acid will remain the technology of choice in almost all of its current applications. This is because leadacid batteries are relatively cheap, the technology is very well proven and robust and there is a well-established infrastructure to recycle batteries. Over the longer term the emergence of mass-produced hybrid and pure electric vehicles may threaten the use of lead in automobiles, and some industrial applications may also be lost to new battery technologies. However, such developments are not expected to have a material impact on the lead market over the next ten years.

# 19.6.1 Gypsum Market

Gypsum is the main ingredient in plaster. Most gypsum that is produced in the world is made into gypsum wallboard. Another major use of gypsum is as a set retarder for portland cement. Synthetic gypsum, made during the flue gas desulphurisation process, can substitute for natural gypsum in wallboard manufacture and is gaining in market share.In 2004, world gypsum production totalled 106 million tonnes. The United States produced the most gypsum at 18 million tonnes. Canada ranked Third, producing 9.3 million tonnes, 7.9 million of which came from Nova Scotia. Approximately half of Nova Scotia's gypsum production came from National Gypsum Canada Limited's Milford quarry, approximately ten kilometres from the Scotia Mine site. This quarry has been operating for over fifty years.

Specifications for gypsum used in wallboard manufacture vary slightly among producers. Typically, they require the gypsum content to be greater than $85 \%$ and the total chloride ion content to be less than 100 ppm (parts per million).

The gypsum industry consists almost exclusively of vertically integrated corporations. Gypsum wallboard manufacturers typically own and operate their own mines. As a consequence, there is no spot market for gypsum.

Several companies have expressed an interest in the gypsum on the Scotia Mine site. A large quantity of gypsum will be removed as waste rock to uncover the zinc and lead Reserves. No formal contracts have yet been signed.

# 19.7 Contracts

No smelter contracts have been established. But, because the demand for concentrate by smelters currently exceed what mines can produce, there should be no trouble establishing smelter contracts at reasonable terms if production can commence within the year. As evidence of that statement, some smelters have recently been paying for zinc concentrate rather than adding a treatment charge (Roberts, 2006).

### 19.7.1 Smelter Returns

For zinc concentrates, a treatment charge must be paid to the smelter for each tonne of concentrate submitted that is linearly related to the spot market zinc price. There is a fixed charge per tonne plus a price escalator clause. The price escalator charge increases linearly for every dollar by which the spot price exceeds a certain value. For example, the benchmark fixed charge for 2005 was \$US 126 (Roberts, 2006). At the end of 2005, the spot market zinc price was $\$$ US 1,900 per tonne of zinc metal. The average price escalator value was $\$$ US 0.14 for every dollar by which the price exceeded $\$$ US 1,400 . Therefore the price escalator clause amounted to $\$$ US 70 per tonne extra ( $\$ 0.14 \times \$ 500$ ), for a total of $\$$ US 196 per tonne of concentrate.

Because of a zinc concentrate shortage in 2005, some smelters were actually paying for zinc concentrate rather than applying a treatment charge.

In addition to the treatment charge, the smelter generally retains $15 \%$ of the zinc metal submitted. In other words, the smelter charges a treatment charge, then pays for $85 \%$ of the zinc metal submitted.Generally, the same arrangement also applies to lead. On average, in 2005, the fixed portion of the treatment charge was \$US 135 and the price escalator value was \$US 0.075 , basis \$US 800 (Roberts, 2006). On top of the treatment charge, the smelter pays for $95 \%$ of the lead metal submitted.

# 19.7.2 Spot Prices

For both zinc and lead, concentrate treatment charges and the price that a smelter will pay for concentrate both depend on the spot markets. The London Metals Exchange (LME) publishes spot market prices for zinc and lead.

At the time of report writing, spot prices for zinc and lead were both at historic high levels (Figure 37 and Figure 38). The zinc and lead spot prices were approximately \$US 3,590 (\$1.63 per pound) and \$US 1,156 per tonne ( $\$ 0.53$ per pound) of refined metal, respectively. The prices of both metals were recovering from near-historic low levels experience in 2002/2003, when zinc and lead spot prices were approximately \$US 800 and \$US 500 per tonne of refined metal, respectively.

From Figure 37, it appears that zinc prices have historically been cyclical. Generally, the price has been fairly steady and increasing at a slow, but steady rate. Every fifteen years, there has been a large price increase that lasted one or two years before falling again to a price that was somewhat higher than the pre-spike price.

Historically, lead prices (Figure 38) have also seemed cyclical, but with not as regular a frequency. High lead prices have not always occurred with high zinc prices.Since 1970:

Low metal prices during the late 1990's and early 2000's led to a swathe of mine closures. The effect on mine output was not limited to closures. Cash flow problems at many mines led to a reduction in exploration and development expenditures, which in turn led to attrition of output at existing operations. These effects are still negatively affecting the current level of output at some mines, though the increase in prices since late 2003 has led to substantial improvement in mine cash flow. Prices increased after 2003 as demand for zinc and lead increased, exceeding what the existing mines could supply.

The current high metal prices are causing new mines to come online and existing ones to expand production. In 2007, just a year away, the greenfield mine project pipeline starts to look much fuller, with some major projects expected to be commissioned. The largest of these is Apex Silver's San Cristobal open-pit project in Bolivia, expected to produce well over $200 \mathrm{kt} / \mathrm{a}$ contained zinc when it reaches full capacity (Roberts, 2006).

If supply starts growing at a faster rate without a corresponding increase in the demand growth rate, prices may begin to decline. Some analysts feel that this is about to occur,starting in 2007 (Roberts, 2006). If they are correct, prices will drop from current levels, but not down to 2002/2003 levels (Table 28).

The anticipated (by some) drop in metal prices will likely be accompanied by a strengthening of the US dollar. Because most of the Scotia Mine's costs would be in Canadian dollars, a strengthening US dollar will soften the blow of decreasing metal prices.

# 19.7.3 Futures Markets

The London Metals Exchange reports the futures market prices for many metals including zinc and lead. For zinc, it reports futures contract prices for the next twenty-seven months. For lead, prices for the next fifteen months are reported. The LME spot and futures prices for July 13, 2006 are reported in Table 35. Futures prices take investment risk, inflation and supply and demand factors into account. Therefore, the expected spot price in say, fifteen months may be different from the 15 -month futures price.

Selling future production is known as hedging. Hedging during falling prices partially insulates the mine's revenue. # 19.8 Water and Sewer

In the past, most of the process water was recycled from the polishing pond. It was pumped from there, through a pipeline back to the mill. Process make-up water, potable water and water for fire suppression was drawn from Gays River using another pump and pipeline. For showers, toilets et cetera, part of that water was filtered in a small, on-site filtration plant. Bottled water was provided for drinking. The proposed mining operation will continue that practice.

A relatively small septic field, of a size appropriate for the care-and-maintenance status of the site, was installed in 2005. Sewage and grey water used to disposed in the tailings pond. If permitted, that practice will be reinstated. If not permitted, it will be a straightforward matter to expand the current septic field.

### 19.9 Environmental Considerations

### 19.9.1 Progressive Reclamation

Reclamation will be an on-going process. The goal will be to minimise the overall land disturbance at any point in time. As much as possible, stripped waste rock and soil will be placed in their final resting places. As mining progresses, final grading and seeding will be carried out as soon as possible. At the end of the mine life, there should be very little reclamation left to carry out.

### 19.9.2 Final Reclamation

A conceptual reclamation plan was submitted during the environmental registration process. It was included as an appendix to the registration document (MGI, 1999). After the mine is decommissioned, it was proposed to allow the pit to fill with ground and surface water to create a deep lake. The temperature of the incoming groundwater will assist in the creation of conditions necessary for the lake waters to undertake seasonal turnovers, resulting in good mixing conditions and maintenance of acceptable dissolved oxygen levels.Prior to the flooding of the pit, the edge areas and slopes that will become the new shoreline will be graded to a maximum allowable 2:1 slope. As appropriate, graded slopes ranging from 3:1 to 5:1 will be created in some areas of the new shoreline. Extending from above the projected water line to depths approaching ten metres, these shores will allow the development of a variety of shoreline habitats (terrestrial, riparian, emergent and submergent) and provide the potential for human recreational use. Submergent and emergent species will assist in the maintenance of water oxygen levels, improve the quality of water reaching the lake and provide a diverse habitat for a variety of terrestrial and aquatic species. The remainder of the area of the bottom of the lake will retain its rugged conditions to provide additional diverse and irregular substrate and subsurface habitat.

When the lake has filled with water to the same elevation as the water in the adjacent River channel, the dyke will be breached in two locations to connect the lake to the Gays River system. Future use of the lake could include artificial stocking with game fish species and/or fresh water aquaculture. However, water and habitat conditions and water quality would first need to be stabilised, and the ramifications of the introduction of non-local game fish carefully examined.

### 19.11 Taxes and Royalties

### 19.11.1 Taxes

Acadian purchased ScoZinc Limited as opposed to the Scotia Mine asset. Purchasing the company rather than the asset complicates the project from a taxation perspective. The ownership history, tax history, etc must be considered. To avoid overly complicating the tax model, the feasibility study was carried out on a project basis rather than a corporate one.

Net income is subject to Federal and Provincial tax at rates of $29.12 \%$ and $16 \%$, respectively. There are several tax-related issues for the project, including Canadian Exploration Expenses (CEE), Canadian Development Expenses (CDE), capital cost allowances (CCA), resource allowance and the Atlantic Investment Tax Credit.

Most Canadian Exploration Expenses (CEE) are 100 \% deductible against mining income. Eligible expenses include exploration, delineation and pre-production development.

Canadian Development Expenses (CDE) are depreciated on a $30 \%$ declining balance. Eligible expenses include the cost of acquiring a mining property in Canada, sinking a mine shaft, main haulage way or similar underground work. It applies to development that is designed to be used for life use of the mine. The mine can deduct up to $30 \%$ of the unclaimed balance in that pool at the end of each year. Unclaimed balances may be carried forward indefinitely.

Capital costs are depreciated according to a capital cost allowance. The rate for most mining equipment is $25 \%$ per year (Class 41). In most cases, the amount deductible in the first year that an asset is acquired is subject to the "half-year" convention, which means that only onehalf of the amount that would be deductible at the normal CCA rate of that asset class can be claimed.

In addition to the normal $25 \%$ rate of depreciation accorded to Class 41 assets, an accelerated capital cost allowance (ACCA) can provide for an additional depreciation allowance of up to $100 \%$ of asset cost. To be eligible for that accelerated depreciation, however, assets must have been acquired before the beginning of commercial production or for major expansions.In the calculation of taxable income, the ACCA deduction is taken after the normal CCA, but before the resource allowance, CEE and CDE. Essentially, the ACCA acts to provide the full write-off of capital costs before a mine starts to pay income tax.

The resource allowance is a tax deduction equal to $25 \%$ of "resource profits." Resource profits are equal to revenue, less operating costs (excluding head office costs, royalties and mining taxes), less capital cost allowances. The resource allowance is being phased-out and will no longer exist after January 1, 2007. Replacing it will be a deduction for corporate income tax purposes of all payments of provincial and other Crown royalties and mining taxes.

An investment tax credit of $10 \%$ is available for capital investments in the Atlantic provinces. A business may deduct ten percent of eligible costs from its federal income tax liability. Eligible investments include qualifying buildings, machinery and equipment used or leased by the taxpayer.

# 19.11.2 Royalties

As stated in Section 3.2, Savage retains a $2 \%$ net smelter return royalty. Acadian entered into an option agreement that would enable it to purchase the royalty for $\$ 1.45$ million at the end of Year 1. That scenario was modelled in the economic analysis. Also, the Province of Nova Scotia levies another $2 \%$ of net revenue royalty. For the purpose of calculating the royalty, net revenue is essentially equal to net smelter return, minus shipping costs.

### 19.12 Capital Cost Estimates

The purchase price for ScoZinc Limited and all of its assets was completed on July 6, 2006 for $\$ \mathrm{CAN} 7.5$ million.

Capital costs are listed in Table 36. General project capital costs include permitting costs, a highway semi-dump truck for concentrate hauling and office equipment.

The mill, which has been under a care and maintenance condition for the past fifteen years, must be cleaned-up and re-commissioned. This will require a relatively minor amount of work (compared against building an entirely new mill). Belts will be replaced and gear oil will be changed. Heat will be applied to all of the motors to drive out any moisture. Bearings will be checked. Circuit breakers will be cleaned. The mill will be thoroughly cleaned and painted. The major capital items include labour for the re-commissioning work, a spare parts inventory and a heating system.

Because the mobile mining equipment will be leased, capital costs for the surface mine will be relatively minor. The most significant cost will be a fleet of four utility pick-up trucks.Pre-production stripping will take approximately two months and cost approximately two million dollars. In the economic analysis, this cost was applied as an operating cost rather than a capital cost.

The overall capital cost for the surface mining operation, excluding pre-production stripping, is $\$ 2.9$ million.

As the surface mine nears completion, the underground mine will start developing. For this work, drill jumbos, scooptrams (load-haul-dump units), a haul truck, utility vehicles, tractors, a compressor, fans, a raise climber, a backfill mixing plant and numerous other pieces of equipment must be purchased. The overall capital cost for the underground mining operation is $\$ 5.6$ million.

# 19.13.2 Electric Power

The Scotia Mine site is currently supplied with three-phase power from the grid. Nova Scotia Power will supply electricity to the site using Rate 22. Peak demand is charged monthly at $\$ 8.01$ per kVA (kilovolt-ampere) per month when customers use their own transformers. Usage is charged at a rate of $\$ 0.048$ per kWh (kilowatt-hour).

### 19.13.3 Ongoing Development

For the surface mine, ongoing development is included in the operating costs and includes stripping, haul road construction and waste rock removal.

For the underground mine, ongoing development includes drift, ramp, cross-cut and raise construction. In total, approximately 4,000 metres of drifts and ramps are required. For an underground mine life of $21 / 2$ years, the average yearly development requirement is 1,600 metres per year. Also, a minimum of 1,000 metres of raising is required over the mine life for a yearly average of 400 metres.

The timing of cash flows determines the amount of initial working capital that is required. Mill repair will take 4-6 months and will start in Month 6 (Table 41). Pre-production stripping will last two months and will begin in Month 10, or as soon as the equipment is delivered. Ore production will begin two months later in Month 12.

It will take approximately two weeks to stockpile enough concentrate for an initial shipment of ten rail cars ( 1,000 tonnes). The initial payment, consisting of $85 \%$ of the concentrate value, is paid thirty days after the concentrate is shipped.

The timing and amount of the final payment depends on several factors. Firstly, the price per pound of metal is determined by averaging the spot metal prices for one month after the concentrate is shipped. Secondly, the average concentrate grade is determined through an exhaustive assaying process. The results are shared with the mine and if they disagree, samples are sent to an independent umpire. This process can take at least 2-3 months. If the mine agrees with the assays, the final payment may be paid in as little as 6-8 weeks after concentrate shipment.

### 19.15 Working Capital

The minimum initial working capital requirement is equal to the minimum cash balance during start-up. This was determined through analysing the project's start-up cash flow, on a month-by-month basis, for the first twenty-four months (Appendix 5). The minimum cash balance was calculated to be $-\$ 5.1$ million, occurring during Month 13. A contingency amount, equal to four months operating costs or $\$ 6.0$ million, should also be added to cover any initial start-up challenges. Therefore, the total initial working capital requirement, including contingency, is $\$ 11.1$ million.

During the project's operation, enough cash will be retained to cover operating costs for the following three months. At a total operating cost of approximately $\$ 1.5$ million per month during surface mining, $\$ 4.5$ million in working capital will continually be maintained. During underground mining, working capital will be maintained at $\$ 5.9$ million.# 19.16 Financing

A sensitivity analysis was carried out to gauge the sensitivity of the project's profitability to changes in metal prices, mine dilution, grade, initial capital costs, operating costs and exchange rate. The profitability indicators that were observed were the project's net present value, using a $8 \%$ discount rate $\left(\mathrm{NPV}_{8 \%}\right)$, and the project's internal rate of return (IRR).

Most parameters were varied to plus or minus $20 \%$ of the base case value. Metal prices were varied to minus $50 \%$ and plus $30 \%$ of the base case values. As one parameter was varied, the other parameters maintained their base case values.

From Figure 41, one can see that factors affecting the revenue, such as metal prices, grade, dilution and exchange rate, had a greater effect on profitability than factors affecting the costs, such as operating costs and initial capital costs. In other words, profitability is most sensitive to changes in metal prices, grade, dilution and exchange rate. It is less sensitive to changes in operating costs and relatively insensitive to changes in initial capital costs. Recall that the surface mobile equipment fleet will be leased.

# 19.19 Discussion of Risks

For both the surface and underground operations, the greatest risk for project profitability is metal price fluctuation. At the time of report writing, zinc and lead prices were at historical highs. For example, the zinc price increased more than three-fold since 2002. Some analysts believe that the zinc price will remain stable and high through 2006 and 2007, then start to decrease. They disagree on when it will start to decrease and by how much. There is the possibility of the zinc price decreasing to \$US 0.50-0.60 per pound by 2010. Other analysts are more bullish regarding metal prices, believing that world demand will outpace supply. Whichever view is correct, the best methods for controlling this risk are mining as quickly as possible and selling a portion of production forward (hedging) while prices are high.

Water inflow to the underground workings provides a less quantifiable, technical risk to the underground portion of the project. Because of the past history of water inflow problems, a "worse case" mine plan has already been adopted. The modified undercut-and-fill mining method that has been adopted for this deposit was designed for very poor ground conditions and offers a high level of protection against potentially unstable ground. Other measures, such as lowering the groundwater table below the level of the mine workings, will also be taken to further alleviate the risk. Because the underground portion of the project begins so far in the future (Year 8), major changes in the underground mining costs and revenue have only a minor effect on the project's net present value.

# 19.21 Mine Life

The surface operation will last almost six years. The underground operation will last more than two years for a total mine life of just over eight years.

The best possibility for extending the mine life lies with the Getty Deposit. Based on a $1.5 \%$ zinc-equivalent cut-off grade ( $1 \% \mathrm{~Pb}=0.6 \% \mathrm{Zn}$ in 1975 using a minimum core length of three metres), resources at the Getty deposit were reported by Hudgins and Lamb (1992) to be 4.5 million tons at an average grade of $1.3 \% \mathrm{~Pb}$ and $1.9 \% \mathrm{Zn} .^{8}$

There are also In-pit Inferred Resources that could potentially extend the surface mine life. The diluted and recoverable In-pit Inferred Resources amounted to 510,000 tonnes containing $2.2 \%$ zinc and $1.1 \%$ lead. The reader should note that there is no guarantee that any of this material can be profitably mined. Grade control sampling during surface mining operations will identify which part(s), if any, of this material could be profitably mined and processed.

Using a combination of surface and underground mining methods, the overall mine life is just over eight years.

The project's capital cost is $\$ 2.9$ million. The surface mobile equipment fleet will be leased. The purchase price for ScoZinc Limited is $\$ 7.5$ million and purchasing Savage's $2 \%$ NSR royalty will cost $\$ 1.45$ million, for a total initial capital cost of $\$ 11.85$ million. The capital cost for the underground operation, starting in Year 6, is $\$ 5.6$ million. The initial working capital requirement, including contingency is $\$ 11.1$ million.

Operating the surface mine and processing plant is expected to cost $\$ 19$ million per year ( $\$ 27$ per tonne of ore or \$US 0.34 per pound of zinc-equivalent). Operating the underground mine and processing plant is expected to cost $\$ 23$ million per year ( $\$ 49$ per tonne of ore or \$US 0.30 per pound of zinc-equivalent).

Net yearly revenue (after smelting costs) during the surface mining operation will be $\$ 43$ million. For the underground operation, yearly revenue will be $\$ 60$ million.

For the base case scenario (\$US 1.10 per pound zinc, \$US 0.45 per pound lead, \$US 0.86 exchange rate), the project's after-tax, net present value using a $8 \%$ discount rate $\left(\mathrm{NPV}_{8 \%\right.$ ) was $\$ 73.6$ million. The internal rate of return was $76 \%$. The payback period was twenty-one months.

Profitability is most sensitive to changes in metal prices, grade, dilution and exchange rate. It is less sensitive to changes in operating costs and relatively insensitive to changes in initial capital costs.

The greatest risk for project profitability is metal price fluctuation. Water inflow to the underground workings provides a less quantifiable, technical risk to the underground portion of the project.

## 21. Recommendations

The technical and economic analysis indicates that the project will be very profitable.
Because the project's profitability is most sensitive to metal prices, production must begin as soon as possible while metal prices remain high.

The Getty Deposit's Resources should be estimated. A feasibility study should also be carried out to determine if the Getty Deposit has any Reserves. This work should cost \$30,000$40,000$.# 22. References

$\square$THIS MEMORANDUM OF LEASE made this 19th day of December, 1985,

BETWEEN:

SEABRIGHT RESOURCES INC., a body corporate, incorporated under the laws of Canada, having an office at Halifax, Nova Scotia ("Lessor")

OF THE FIRST PART

- and -

NOVA RECREATION DEVELOPMENT COMPANY LIMITED, a body corporate, incorporated under the laws of the Province of Nova Scotia, having an office at Yarmouth, Nova Scotia ("Lessee")

OF THE SECOND PART

THIS INDENTURE WITNESSETH THAT:

1. IN CONSIDERATION of the rents, covenants and agreements herein, the Lessor demises to the Lessee the sand ("Sand") presently on and under the lands of the Lessor located at Gays River, Nova Scotia and described in Schedule "A", ("Demised Premises") which demise shall include:

(a) the right to mine by surface operation only and to take away the Sand from the Demised Premises;(b) the right to enter upon and to occupy the Demised Premises as may be required for the purpose of mining and processing the Sand;
(c) the right to construct or erect such buildings or structures upon the Demised Premises as may be required for the purpose of mining and processing the Sand;
(d) the right to store and to stockpile the Sand upon the Demised Premises;
(e) the right to wash or otherwise make merchantable the Sand at locations approved by Seabright on the Demised Premises;
(f) to bring on to the Demised Premises such equipment, vehicles and other machinery as may be required for the purpose of mining and processing the Sand.

Reservations and Exceptions

Provided, however, the following are also excepted from the grant to the Lessee in respect of the Demised Premises:
(a) Two million tonnes of lower grade Sand reserved to the Lessor for the purpose of carrying out its operations;
(b) such of the Sand as is or may be required for the support of any building, shaft, mine, tailings pond, roadway or other structure presently standing or which may hereafter be constructed upon the Demised Premises, together with such reasonable surrounding areas as the Lessor shall require;
(c) such of the Demised Premises as may at any time and from time to time be required by the Lessor for the purpose of carrying out its operations upon the Demised Premises including without limitation the rehabilitation and operation of the lead/zinc mine and the reactivation of the processing mill located on the Demised Premises.Provided, however, that the Lessor and the Lessee shall use their best efforts to carry out their respective operations in a manner compatible one to the other on the Demised Premises.

Subject; however, that wherever the grant of the Demised Premises to the Lessee hereunder shall, in the Lessor's reasonable opinion, in any way interfere with or affect any of the operations of the Lessor upon the Demised Premises this grant of the Demised Premises shall be limited and restricted so as to ensure that such operations of the Lessor are not interferred with or affected in any way;

Term

2. THE TERM for which the Lessee shall hold the Demised Premises is the period of Ninety-Nine (99) years, commencing on the 1st day of January, 1986, herein called the "Commencement Date" and ending on the 31st day of December, 2084, both dates inclusive, and herein called the "Term".

Rent/Royalty

3. THE RENT that the Lessee shall pay is in accordance with the conditions and terms set out in Paragraph 3 of the Lease dated December 19, 1985.

4. Any notice required or permitted hereunder shall be sufficiently given if by hand or sent by prepaid registered mail as follows:

This Lease may be executed in separate counterparts, each of which when so executed shall together constitute one Lease.

This Lease may be assigned by either party.
